com.randallscharpf.java.jmorsecoding.base.symbolsets

Class SymbolSetBase

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.randallscharpf.java.jmorsecoding.base.symbolsets.SymbolSetBase
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    MorseSymbolSet
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    ExtendedInternationalSymbolSet, InternationalSymbolSet

    public abstract class SymbolSetBase
extends java.lang.Object
implements MorseSymbolSet
    A concrete implementation of a MorseSymbolSet implemented using an enum. Subclasses can, by linking to the appropriate enum class, use the sequencing and lookup implementations provided by this class.
    This class is most efficient when the linked enum class never changes. Each time an implemented method is called on a new class, a cache is internally built in O(S) time, where S is the number of elements in the enum linked. The total size of stored caches is also O(S). Subsequent operations are much faster and at most linear in the size of the input to the function.
    Since:
    1.0

      • getSymbolEnumClass

        protected abstract java.lang.Class<? extends java.lang.Enum<? extends SymbolSetBase.MorseSymbol>> getSymbolEnumClass()
        Gives the class of an enumeration containing all the symbols that can be translated by this set. Includes all translatable prosigns and characters. The enumeration class must implement the SymbolSetBase.MorseSymbol interface.
        Implementing this method associates the implementations in this class (SymbolSetBase) with the data in the subclass while allowing subclasses to package their data in the form of an enumeration: the implicit superclass of Java's enumerations prevents the subclass itself from holding the data in this way. This method is not intended to be used outside of this class (SymbolSetBase).
        Returns:
        the enum of symbols that this set supports translating
        Since:
        1.0

      • getAvailableProsigns

        public java.lang.String[] getAvailableProsigns()
        Gives the names of the prosigns registered as symbols in this set. The name of a prosign is typically related to the action it performs in communication or the written symbol used in transcripts of conversations to indicate that the prosign was sent. The names in this array must be such that calling MorseSymbolSet.getPlayableForProsign(java.lang.String) on any str that is an element of this array will give a valid PlayableMorseUnit and not instead throw an error.
        Specified by:
        getAvailableProsigns in interface MorseSymbolSet
        Returns:
        an array of the names of all prosigns supported by this symbol set
        Since:
        1.0

      • getPlayableForProsign

        public PlayableMorseUnit getPlayableForProsign(java.lang.String prosignName)
        Returns a unit that plays a prosign. The prosign is followed by a word gap. The input string and prosign name (as listed in MorseSymbolSet.getAvailableProsigns() must be approximately the same, but the choice of comparison function is left open to implementers. A good choice for implementers is to compare the strings in lowercase, and users of this function should prefer to provide as parameter the exact string that appears in the list of available prosigns.
        Specified by:
        getPlayableForProsign in interface MorseSymbolSet
        Parameters:
        prosignName - a string giving the action represented by the prosign
        Returns:
        a gap-terminated PlayableMorseUnit for the requested prosign
        Since:
        1.0

      • getPlayableForString

        public PlayableMorseUnit getPlayableForString(java.lang.String str)
        Returns a unit that plays the each of the characters in the given string in order, with proper separation. The string is terminated with a word gap so that it becomes a discrete message, unless the end of the provided string is whitespace.
        Specified by:
        getPlayableForString in interface MorseSymbolSet
        Parameters:

        Returns:

        Since:

      • standardizeChar

        protected char standardizeChar(char c)
        Maps characters that should be considered the same to some common character. For example, Morse Code does not distinguish between capital and lowercase letters, so the characters 'a' and 'A' should be mapped to some character X which is the same for each of them. In addition, the symbol set must be configured to map the character X to the appropriate sets of dots and dashes for both 'a' and 'A'. The default implementation of this function simply converts the character to lowercase, but subclasses should override the function if the translation they use implies a different equivalence relation among characters (where two characters are equivalent in the relation if they are represented by the same set of dots and dashes).
        Parameters:
        c - a character for which to determine an equivalence class
        Returns:
        the character from the equivalence class of the input in the symbol set

      • standardizeString

        protected java.lang.String standardizeString(java.lang.String str)
        Maps prosign names that should be considered the same to some common string. For example, the prosigns "STARTING SIGNAL" and "starting signal" are probably the same, so they should be mapped to some string X which is the same for each of them. In addition, the symbol set must be configured to map the string X to the appropriate sets of dots and dashes for that starting signal prosign. The default implementation of this function simply converts the string to lowercase, but subclasses should override the function if the translation they use implies a different equivalence relation among strings (where two strings are equivalent in the relation if they name the same prosign).
        Parameters:
        str - a string for which to determine an equivalence class
        Returns:
        the string from the equivalence class of the input in the symbol set
